1
00:00:09,240 --> 00:00:15,000
In the remote jungles of Papua New Guinea, an international team of scientists and filmmakers

2
00:00:15,040 --> 00:00:18,480
has been searching for rare and endangered creatures.

3
00:00:21,560 --> 00:00:25,880
We could find something really, really spectacular inside here.

4
00:00:25,920 --> 00:00:27,440
I guess that's the hope.

5
00:00:28,360 --> 00:00:31,800
Two weeks in and they've made an impressive start.

6
00:00:34,360 --> 00:00:35,960
What an extraordinary looking fish.

7
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:40,040
They've found the weird... I have no idea what that will become.

8
00:00:40,080 --> 00:00:44,960
The wonderful. Now you can really see how tiny he is like compared to your thumb.

9
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:48,000
And discovered animals unknown to science.

10
00:00:48,040 --> 00:00:53,720
I'll bet you any money that wasp right there that's walking along that leaf is a new species,

11
00:00:53,760 --> 00:00:54,960
I bet you any money.

12
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:58,120
They've hunted high and low.

13
00:00:58,160 --> 00:01:04,080
Now, beneath the forest floor, Steve Backshall is pushing deep into a cave,

14
00:01:04,120 --> 00:01:07,240
one of the few places on Earth where no-one has been before.

15
00:01:10,080 --> 00:01:13,040
I've never seen anything like this before in my life.

16
00:01:13,080 --> 00:01:15,680
This is extraordinary!

17
00:01:41,360 --> 00:01:45,120
Just above Australia in the western Pacific

18
00:01:45,160 --> 00:01:47,760
lies Papua New Guinea.

19
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:52,920
Cloaked in dense rainforest, these valleys are among the most isolated on the planet.

20
00:01:56,240 --> 00:02:03,000
The main base camp is on the slopes of an extinct volcano, Mount Bosavi.

21
00:02:03,040 --> 00:02:07,480
Further east, a smaller team is on the island of New Britain.

22
00:02:07,520 --> 00:02:11,720
They're exploring an underground river cave, mapping it as they go.

23
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:15,000
This is one of the most remote, inaccessible places on the planet

24
00:02:15,040 --> 00:02:20,080
and there genuinely are dark corners of Papua New Guinea that no human being has ever been to before.

25
00:02:20,120 --> 00:02:24,440
This place is absolutely ripe for exploration.

26
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:26,000
It's risky.

27
00:02:26,040 --> 00:02:30,560
Just to get in means abseiling 80 metres to the cave entrance.

28
00:02:34,280 --> 00:02:38,280
Oh, it's pretty nippy, isn't it?

29
00:02:38,560 --> 00:02:43,160
Steve Backshall is the expedition climber, caver and naturalist.

30
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:46,920
Oh, this is unbelievable!

31
00:02:46,960 --> 00:02:49,960
Look at that.What an unbelievable amount of water.

32
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,200
Welcome to Mageni river cave.

33
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:57,600
He's joined the Anglo-French team who first discovered this cave.

34
00:02:57,640 --> 00:02:59,600
The locals call it Mageni.

35
00:03:01,280 --> 00:03:06,440
They're led by pioneering British caver Dave Nixon, known as Moose.

36
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:10,240
I remember coming up here

37
00:03:10,280 --> 00:03:14,600
really, really excited, not knowing what was at the top.

38
00:03:14,640 --> 00:03:18,080
Well, it makes you feel so alive.

39
00:03:18,120 --> 00:03:23,320
Their aim is to press further into this uncharted cave

40
00:03:23,360 --> 00:03:25,920
and map passages never seen before by man.

41
00:03:27,640 --> 00:03:29,560
Plus 5.7.

42
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:36,200
Lucy is bouncing a laser off the walls of the tunnel so we can figure out how big it all is.

43
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:41,680
That's the whole purpose of surveying, it's just to map out the size of the caverns.

44
00:03:41,720 --> 00:03:46,240
Jean-Paul, this joint is developed on

45
00:03:46,280 --> 00:03:50,280
50 degrees, 230. 50, 230.

46
00:03:54,560 --> 00:04:01,360
What fires them is the hope of finding a new, undiscovered route right through the mountain.

47
00:04:09,920 --> 00:04:14,600
700 miles west in the shadow of Mount Bosavi lies the base camp.

48
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:22,360
A cluster of makeshift huts is home to the wildlife filmmakers, the expedition medic,

49
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:24,840
expert trackers,

50
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:26,280
cooks...

51
00:04:27,280 --> 00:04:30,080
and, at its heart, the scientists.

52
00:04:30,120 --> 00:04:33,640
Leading them is Dr George McGavin.

53
00:04:34,520 --> 00:04:37,880
I'm heading up a team of scientists, experts in their own field.

54
00:04:37,920 --> 00:04:44,080
Our aim is to document what animals live in and around this giant, extinct volcano,

55
00:04:44,120 --> 00:04:48,200
and also to search for any new species, and there must be hundreds.

56
00:04:49,200 --> 00:04:52,720
The cooks are preparing the dinner,

57
00:04:52,760 --> 00:04:55,280
when their fishing nets land something bigger

58
00:04:55,320 --> 00:04:56,800
than they'd bargained for.

59
00:04:58,440 --> 00:05:00,960
George is on hand to help.

60
00:05:03,440 --> 00:05:04,840
It's a crocodile, I think.

61
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:17,200
Croc expert Paul O'Dowd has to work fast but carefully.

62
00:05:17,240 --> 00:05:20,080
It's really essential that we secure the front end,

63
00:05:20,120 --> 00:05:22,320
and the jaws have to be tied shut otherwise

64
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:24,400
they could take somebody's hand off.

65
00:05:24,440 --> 00:05:26,240
But she's really growling,

66
00:05:26,280 --> 00:05:28,640
you can feel that "grrrr" in her throat.

67
00:05:28,680 --> 00:05:31,320
She's not a happy croc at all.

68
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:35,960
Almost unnoticed in the net, there's a venomous catfish.

69
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:37,920
There's a big fish here

70
00:05:37,960 --> 00:05:41,880
and the spine is loaded with very nasty toxins,

71
00:05:41,920 --> 00:05:46,480
and if that jabs into Paul's hand or my hand, not nice,

72
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:48,840
you'd be a very sick person.

73
00:05:48,880 --> 00:05:52,200
Actually, George, maybe with your free hand

74
00:05:52,240 --> 00:05:55,560
could you just sort of make sure that this...?

75
00:05:55,600 --> 00:05:59,000
That's the way.It's not everyday that you have to restrain

76
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:01,560
a large freshwater crocodile

77
00:06:01,600 --> 00:06:06,680
while holding a toxic spine of a catfish in your other hand.

78
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:09,960
Out of the net, the crocodile is now free to go.

79
00:06:13,080 --> 00:06:14,880
Fantastic, happy ending.

80
00:06:14,920 --> 00:06:17,320
She's off, she's safe.

81
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:19,160
Well done, mate.

82
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:27,840
It's all in a day's work.

83
00:06:27,880 --> 00:06:30,960
But George's main job is running the jungle lab.

84
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:34,280
This is an absolute monster.

85
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:40,000
His team has already discovered 17 new species

86
00:06:40,040 --> 00:06:43,600
and catalogued hundreds of other animals.

87
00:06:48,960 --> 00:06:53,000
What have you got there, Jack?The latest creature has just been found

88
00:06:53,040 --> 00:06:54,760
on a tree right next to the lab.

89
00:06:54,800 --> 00:06:57,200
It's quite clearly a group of three caterpillars

90
00:06:57,240 --> 00:06:58,520
on that vine of some sort.

91
00:06:58,560 --> 00:07:00,640
I have no idea what that will become.

92
00:07:00,680 --> 00:07:04,640
It looks almost as if it's a snake.

93
00:07:04,680 --> 00:07:07,680
You know, it's quite disturbing if you're a bird I suppose.

94
00:07:07,720 --> 00:07:12,520
As an extra defence, two of them will thrash around like that.

95
00:07:12,560 --> 00:07:16,640
Well, what I think we should do is we should put them in a cage

96
00:07:16,680 --> 00:07:21,600
and just observe them, but it could be weeks until they actually pupate,

97
00:07:21,640 --> 00:07:25,640
which is the only way of finding out what they'll become.

98
00:07:28,320 --> 00:07:31,400
Some animals are showy,

99
00:07:31,440 --> 00:07:35,280
others hide away hoping they won't be seen.

100
00:07:39,160 --> 00:07:44,600
This one's cover has just been blown by wildlife cameraman Gordon Buchanan.

101
00:07:48,360 --> 00:07:50,080
Oh, do you know what that is?

102
00:07:50,120 --> 00:07:52,480
It's a beautiful fruit dove.

103
00:07:54,920 --> 00:07:57,640
That's what it's called, that's not my name for it.

104
00:07:57,680 --> 00:07:59,400
I love all the names of...

105
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:01,640
especially birds in Papua New Guinea.

106
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:04,600
You've got all these magnificent bird of paradise,

107
00:08:04,640 --> 00:08:07,240
magnificent rifle bird, the superb fruit dove,

108
00:08:07,280 --> 00:08:10,400
the beautiful fruit dove, they're all very descriptive.

109
00:08:10,440 --> 00:08:15,040
Unbelievably camouflaged sitting there. Such a good find.

110
00:08:18,040 --> 00:08:21,400
It's one of the jungle's more unassuming characters,

111
00:08:21,440 --> 00:08:25,120
but Gordon has his sights set on a far more flamboyant bird.

112
00:08:26,680 --> 00:08:30,040
Personally, I want to find Birds of Paradise.

113
00:08:30,080 --> 00:08:33,520
They are the most iconic bird family on the planet.

114
00:08:33,560 --> 00:08:36,800
They have fascinated every ornithologist, every naturalist

115
00:08:36,840 --> 00:08:40,520
since they were first discovered 400 years ago. I'm no different.

116
00:08:40,560 --> 00:08:42,880
Gordon's mission is to record

117
00:08:42,920 --> 00:08:46,720
one of the most extraordinary rituals in nature,

118
00:08:46,760 --> 00:08:50,200
the mating display of the Bird of Paradise.

119
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,600
Underground, Steve and the caving team

120
00:08:57,640 --> 00:09:00,560
are battling against the white water river.

121
00:09:12,440 --> 00:09:14,360
Steve is the team's naturalist.

122
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:18,880
Even in a cave, some creatures still survive.

123
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:23,600
These cave crickets are real specialists

124
00:09:23,640 --> 00:09:25,360
at this kind of environment.

125
00:09:25,400 --> 00:09:30,000
They have tiny little eyes but really almost all of their senses

126
00:09:30,040 --> 00:09:32,280
are in these gigantic antenna.

127
00:09:32,320 --> 00:09:36,080
Look at that, I mean that is probably six times the length of the body.

128
00:09:36,120 --> 00:09:39,480
They're tactile. They tap around a bit in front of the cave

129
00:09:39,520 --> 00:09:42,840
just feeling its way, and also pick up chemical signals.

130
00:09:42,880 --> 00:09:45,320
So it works like a nose, like eyes

131
00:09:45,360 --> 00:09:49,160
and also a bit like a blind man's white stick as well.

132
00:09:49,200 --> 00:09:51,600
I think this one here is a female.

133
00:09:51,640 --> 00:09:56,040
Possibly the least pretty-looking girl in the world.

134
00:09:56,080 --> 00:09:58,360
In total darkness, looks are irrelevant.

135
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:02,280
Above ground, appearances can be everything.

136
00:10:02,320 --> 00:10:06,440
Bird expert Jack Dumbacher's found a King Bird of Paradise.

137
00:10:06,480 --> 00:10:08,360
I would like to take a blood sample.

138
00:10:08,400 --> 00:10:11,560
So there's a small vein that runs right under the arm here,

139
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:13,440
we can get the DNA from the blood.

140
00:10:13,480 --> 00:10:15,800
We can use that for genetic studies,

141
00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:19,280
and we can also use it to test whether or not the birds

142
00:10:19,320 --> 00:10:22,480
are carrying malaria or other blood diseases.

143
00:10:22,520 --> 00:10:28,880
Keeping a record of all the animals is expedition photographer Ulla Lohmann.

144
00:10:28,920 --> 00:10:31,760
I've never seen colours like that.

145
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:33,320
I mean me being a photographer

146
00:10:33,360 --> 00:10:36,520
I love colours and especially when the light is just breaking

147
00:10:36,560 --> 00:10:38,880
into it's feathers, it's just magnificent.

148
00:10:38,920 --> 00:10:42,320
All these colours are to impress the female and their mating display.

149
00:10:42,360 --> 00:10:45,720
They flash all these colours, they have a special dance that they do

150
00:10:45,760 --> 00:10:47,160
and the female is very drab

151
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:50,120
so she doesn't have any of these specialised colours,

152
00:10:50,160 --> 00:10:51,480
just the male has these.

153
00:10:53,600 --> 00:10:57,080
Completing the look areelaborate tail wires

154
00:10:57,120 --> 00:10:59,680
that play a big part in his courtship display.

155
00:10:59,720 --> 00:11:03,720
It's an important find, proof that Birds of Paradise

156
00:11:03,760 --> 00:11:05,880
live in this patch of forest.

157
00:11:05,920 --> 00:11:11,480
HIGH PITCHED SQUEAKING

158
00:11:11,520 --> 00:11:14,080
What have you got, Jack? Good to see you, Gordon.

159
00:11:16,040 --> 00:11:18,680
Caught up in that net.

160
00:11:18,720 --> 00:11:21,840
Let me just get my hand down in there so that he can't get away.

161
00:11:21,880 --> 00:11:25,160
Oh, a king! Oh, you beauty.

162
00:11:25,200 --> 00:11:27,600
Oh, my goodness me.

163
00:11:27,640 --> 00:11:29,880
They are quite incredible.

164
00:11:29,920 --> 00:11:34,520
All the Birds of Paradise are almost beyond belief.

165
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:37,160
Jack releases it just where it was found.

166
00:11:39,720 --> 00:11:43,000
Well, it looks like he's happiest on a vertical perch.

167
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:47,240
Birds of Paradise look stunning,

168
00:11:47,280 --> 00:11:50,960
but even more impressive is their courtship dance.

169
00:11:52,640 --> 00:11:56,720
Catching this on camera will draw Gordon deep into the jungle.

170
00:12:03,880 --> 00:12:06,400
These forests are now under threat.

171
00:12:06,440 --> 00:12:09,560
There's big money to be made from tropical timber.

172
00:12:11,240 --> 00:12:16,400
This forest giant has been growing here for between 100 and 150 years.

173
00:12:16,440 --> 00:12:19,800
The value of this tree when it's cut down to the landowner,

174
00:12:19,840 --> 00:12:23,640
the man who owns this tree, is only about £8.

175
00:12:23,680 --> 00:12:27,560
When it's prepared and shipped out as timber in the UK

176
00:12:27,600 --> 00:12:29,760
it will fetch £1,000 or more.

177
00:12:29,800 --> 00:12:32,880
Somebody is making a great deal of cash,

178
00:12:32,920 --> 00:12:36,120
and it's not the people who own this tree.

179
00:12:38,320 --> 00:12:42,600
Papua New Guinea's forests are peppered with hundreds of remote tribes.

180
00:12:44,880 --> 00:12:47,560
It's those tribes and not the government

181
00:12:47,600 --> 00:12:49,600
who own the land and the trees.

182
00:12:49,640 --> 00:12:53,520
Tribal elders have a difficult decision to make...

183
00:12:53,560 --> 00:12:56,000
Keep their forests,

184
00:12:56,040 --> 00:12:58,240
or sell the trees to the loggers.

185
00:13:01,560 --> 00:13:03,920
If we keep forests like this intact,

186
00:13:03,960 --> 00:13:05,760
we will reduce our chances

187
00:13:05,800 --> 00:13:07,880
of suffering the worst effects

188
00:13:08,040 --> 00:13:12,000
of global climate change and we'll save between 60 and 80%

189
00:13:12,040 --> 00:13:14,000
of all the world's species.

190
00:13:14,040 --> 00:13:15,800
For me, it's a no-brainer.

191
00:13:24,840 --> 00:13:28,720
In the cave, progress is slow and exhausting.

192
00:13:28,760 --> 00:13:30,520
They need to stop and refuel.

193
00:13:30,560 --> 00:13:33,360
The French have brought cheese,

194
00:13:33,400 --> 00:13:35,280
and the Brits,

195
00:13:35,320 --> 00:13:37,040
baked beans.

196
00:13:37,080 --> 00:13:40,000
Oh, please tell me you're not eating cold baked beans?

197
00:13:40,040 --> 00:13:42,960
What's the matter with you, man? Oh, you're all wrong!

198
00:13:44,040 --> 00:13:45,880
I'll have some of that, that's mine.

199
00:13:48,120 --> 00:13:51,080
No, the cheese, cheese is good.

200
00:13:51,120 --> 00:13:55,680
Oh, no, that absolutely turns my stomach.

201
00:13:55,720 --> 00:14:01,840
Smell that. This is actually pretty good for us.

202
00:14:01,880 --> 00:14:05,360
I mean we've really just been having a chocolate bar for lunch most days.

203
00:14:05,400 --> 00:14:09,000
To actually stop and have cheese and crackers, it's luxury!

204
00:14:09,040 --> 00:14:12,440
YORKSHIRE ACCENT: Eee, you don't know you're born, lad!

205
00:14:14,880 --> 00:14:18,520
From base camp, two boats head upstream.

206
00:14:18,560 --> 00:14:21,520
Gordon's first stop on his search for Birds of Paradise

207
00:14:21,560 --> 00:14:24,800
is a remote village where the feathers are used for costumes.

208
00:14:24,840 --> 00:14:29,760
Also on their way are George and expedition medic Jane Stevenson.

209
00:14:35,840 --> 00:14:39,880
The boats' engines disturb a colony of bats roosting in the treetops.

210
00:14:45,280 --> 00:14:47,120
This is quite spectacular.

211
00:14:47,160 --> 00:14:51,240
These are flying foxes, they're the largest bats on the planet.

212
00:14:51,280 --> 00:14:53,520
They are just amazing, look at the size of them.

213
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:57,640
They must have a wingspan of about that.

214
00:14:57,680 --> 00:15:00,800
They eat, I think it's exclusively fruit.

215
00:15:00,840 --> 00:15:04,080
When they eat the fruit they pass through the seeds,

216
00:15:04,120 --> 00:15:06,320
so they are pretty much the species

217
00:15:06,360 --> 00:15:10,560
that is responsible for keeping this forest living and growing.

218
00:15:12,200 --> 00:15:14,800
Oh, wow!

219
00:15:29,600 --> 00:15:34,520
Fogomaiyu village is dominated by the extinct volcano Mount Bosavi.

220
00:15:34,560 --> 00:15:37,560
Contact with outsiders is rare.

221
00:15:39,680 --> 00:15:42,240
Yeah, it's an unbelievable welcome,

222
00:15:42,280 --> 00:15:46,720
you're sort of quite overwhelmed about somewhere like this

223
00:15:46,760 --> 00:15:48,880
and so many people just turn out

224
00:15:48,920 --> 00:15:51,280
with just big smiles on their face.

225
00:15:51,320 --> 00:15:52,880
Is he a big man in the village?

226
00:15:52,920 --> 00:15:55,360
This man?He's the chief.Oh, I see.

227
00:15:57,200 --> 00:15:58,840
His name is Chief Ayambo.

228
00:15:58,880 --> 00:16:01,440
These villagers know more than anyone

229
00:16:01,480 --> 00:16:04,640
about Birds of Paradise and where they display.

230
00:16:04,680 --> 00:16:06,080
Thank you, thank you.

231
00:16:08,040 --> 00:16:11,560
Hello. It's Gordon, pleased to meet you.

232
00:16:11,600 --> 00:16:15,280
These feathers are from Birds of Paradise?

233
00:16:15,320 --> 00:16:17,160
Cassowary, OK.

234
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:22,520
It's a very poor village of just 500 people.

235
00:16:22,560 --> 00:16:25,240
Medicines are in short supply

236
00:16:25,280 --> 00:16:27,680
and there's been a severe outbreak of malaria.

237
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:32,280
Here in this particular village one of the biggest problems is access.

238
00:16:32,320 --> 00:16:34,200
They can't get out to hospitals,

239
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:35,920
they can't get out to clinics,

240
00:16:35,960 --> 00:16:38,120
they can't get medicines brought in,

241
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:41,080
and everything is so expensive for them that health

242
00:16:41,120 --> 00:16:44,960
has actually had to take a back seat really, to just pure survival.

243
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:47,600
While Jane sets up a makeshift clinic,

244
00:16:47,640 --> 00:16:49,720
George meets the village elders

245
00:16:49,760 --> 00:16:53,640
to find out what the future holds for them and their forest.

246
00:16:53,680 --> 00:16:56,760
First of all, I want to thank you very much

247
00:16:56,800 --> 00:17:01,720
for us being able to be here in this fantastic forest land of yours.

248
00:17:01,760 --> 00:17:08,000
It has been a great honour. You own a huge area of valuable land.

249
00:17:08,040 --> 00:17:11,960
You could sell your land, you could sell your trees.

250
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:15,760
What do you want to happen, what's the way forward?

251
00:17:30,400 --> 00:17:34,160
Well, you know, you're sort of stuck because you want certain things,

252
00:17:34,200 --> 00:17:38,040
you want to pay for education and healthcare and soap and things,

253
00:17:38,080 --> 00:17:41,080
but you don't have the means of earning the cash.

254
00:17:53,880 --> 00:17:56,320
How many children die here?

255
00:18:02,840 --> 00:18:08,360
At Jane's clinic, a concerned mother has brought in her feverish child.

256
00:18:08,400 --> 00:18:10,920
We need to be sponging this baby down.

257
00:18:10,960 --> 00:18:15,280
I'm going to test the baby for malaria but it probably is malaria.

258
00:18:15,320 --> 00:18:19,240
It's one of the biggest killers in the tropics.

259
00:18:19,280 --> 00:18:23,120
Out here, mosquito nets are virtually non-existent.

260
00:18:25,360 --> 00:18:27,240
Can you see there's two lines there?

261
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:34,840
Jane's test confirms her worst fears.

262
00:18:34,880 --> 00:18:38,560
He is particularly vulnerable now. He has a raging fever

263
00:18:38,600 --> 00:18:42,920
and he has the worst type of malaria strain.

264
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:46,480
This is today's dose,

265
00:18:46,520 --> 00:18:48,120
as soon as possible.

266
00:18:48,160 --> 00:18:51,000
Although the baby is getting quite upset with this

267
00:18:51,040 --> 00:18:52,800
it is absolutely the best thing.

268
00:18:52,840 --> 00:18:55,240
This will potentially save his life

269
00:18:55,280 --> 00:18:59,400
and without this there is a very high chance that he will die.

270
00:19:18,280 --> 00:19:23,480
A mile into the mountain, rescue from outside is next to impossible.

271
00:19:23,520 --> 00:19:26,080
The water here is very fast-flowing and deep,

272
00:19:26,120 --> 00:19:28,320
that's why we're wearing lifejackets,

273
00:19:28,360 --> 00:19:31,520
because really if you're spending a lot of time in the water

274
00:19:31,560 --> 00:19:35,200
try not to get too cold, and really just battling against the flow.

275
00:19:35,240 --> 00:19:40,400
Moose has put in these lines so you could traverse across safely.

276
00:19:42,440 --> 00:19:46,360
Whoa, it's pretty faster here, Moose.

277
00:19:46,400 --> 00:19:49,960
Don't want to get swept away there, do you?Watch your feet.

278
00:19:55,640 --> 00:19:58,760
Oh, it's like the North Sea. Freezing.

279
00:20:08,240 --> 00:20:13,160
Forcing themselves against the flow, the team press on into the darkness.

280
00:20:21,440 --> 00:20:23,880
Here he is. This is a dwarf kingfisher.

281
00:20:23,920 --> 00:20:27,560
You can see just how small he is.

282
00:20:27,600 --> 00:20:32,520
George is back at work with the other scientists.

283
00:20:32,560 --> 00:20:36,320
Look at that. It's really fast.

284
00:20:36,360 --> 00:20:40,480
Their work is vital if they are to prove this jungle is worth saving.

285
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:44,840
Alanna Maltby is the bat expert.

286
00:20:44,880 --> 00:20:47,760
She's made another important find.

287
00:20:49,520 --> 00:20:53,160
This is the second potential new species of bat.

288
00:20:53,200 --> 00:20:55,280
Amazing.Yeah, really is amazing.

289
00:20:55,320 --> 00:20:59,640
It's really unusual to find new mammals and new bats,

290
00:20:59,680 --> 00:21:03,520
and to have two potential new species in the course of a couple of weeks,

291
00:21:03,560 --> 00:21:06,800
that's just that's like nothing I've ever come across.

292
00:21:06,840 --> 00:21:11,080
The frog man has been kept busy too.

293
00:21:11,120 --> 00:21:16,280
You could spend the whole day trying to catch one of these things.

294
00:21:16,320 --> 00:21:22,080
But this is yet another frog which Alan Allison has never seen before.

295
00:21:22,120 --> 00:21:24,080
It's an interesting little guy

296
00:21:24,120 --> 00:21:27,520
because I'm almost certain that it's a new species.

297
00:21:27,560 --> 00:21:29,680
This is exactly why I'm here.

298
00:21:29,720 --> 00:21:34,280
We're seeing animals in a 100 years time might not even be here.

299
00:21:37,120 --> 00:21:39,440
The scientists will report their findings

300
00:21:39,480 --> 00:21:41,480
to the government of Papua New Guinea

301
00:21:41,520 --> 00:21:45,600
to lend support in protecting Mount Bosavi's weird and wonderful wildlife.

302
00:21:47,160 --> 00:21:50,160
This is amazing, this is a really strange world.

303
00:21:50,200 --> 00:21:52,720
Here is a beetle larva.

304
00:21:52,760 --> 00:21:55,360
Over there, we have a tiny bat.

305
00:21:55,400 --> 00:22:00,400
So here is an animal with a backbone that is a fraction the size of this.

306
00:22:00,440 --> 00:22:04,600
Alanna, can I just compare the size of that bat

307
00:22:04,640 --> 00:22:07,080
to the size of this insect?

308
00:22:07,120 --> 00:22:10,880
Which one do you think is more beautiful, George?

309
00:22:10,920 --> 00:22:12,920
I have to confess, Alanna,

310
00:22:12,960 --> 00:22:16,560
on this occasion the bat does win it hands down.

311
00:22:16,600 --> 00:22:19,880
Even I couldn't really love this thing.

312
00:22:27,760 --> 00:22:32,040
In Mageni, the only respite from the deafening river

313
00:22:32,080 --> 00:22:35,320
is to enter one of its many side caverns.

314
00:22:35,360 --> 00:22:41,800
Wow, this is nothing like any other cave we've seen so far at Mageni.

315
00:22:41,840 --> 00:22:43,600
It's quiet, relatively dry.

316
00:22:43,640 --> 00:22:46,360
We can talk to each other without shouting.

317
00:22:46,400 --> 00:22:48,480
Yeah, it's incredible, isn't it?

318
00:22:48,520 --> 00:22:51,360
Looks at these stals, they're fantastic.

319
00:22:51,400 --> 00:22:53,320
Check this out here, Steve.

320
00:22:53,360 --> 00:22:56,200
See this formation, you've got a column that's formed

321
00:22:56,240 --> 00:22:58,400
where a stalactite has met a stalagmite.

322
00:22:58,440 --> 00:23:00,280
This is deposited on a mud floor,

323
00:23:00,320 --> 00:23:03,600
but can you see how it's all fractured and broken there?

324
00:23:03,640 --> 00:23:07,920
That's almost certainly as a result of earth movement, earthquakes.

325
00:23:07,960 --> 00:23:10,320
What do you think it would be like down here if...

326
00:23:10,360 --> 00:23:12,920
It would be terrifying, really would be terrifying.

327
00:23:15,600 --> 00:23:20,080
It's been a long day of caving and, two miles into the mountain,

328
00:23:20,120 --> 00:23:22,840
they have to find somewhere to sleep.

329
00:23:31,200 --> 00:23:33,120
It's dusk in the village.

330
00:23:33,160 --> 00:23:36,440
Tomorrow, Gordon will set off in search of Birds of Paradise.

331
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:39,400
But tonight, the village elders have allowed him

332
00:23:39,440 --> 00:23:41,000
to see their head dresses.

333
00:23:46,600 --> 00:23:48,280
So this is from the Ragi Bird of Paradise.

334
00:23:48,320 --> 00:23:51,160
You are correct, some... Raggianna.

335
00:23:51,200 --> 00:23:54,120
Yeah, see I know what

336
00:23:54,160 --> 00:23:55,680
I'm talking about!

337
00:23:59,120 --> 00:24:03,120
OK. It's like having a personal dresser.

338
00:24:03,160 --> 00:24:08,320
So do they use these headdresses for ceremonies?For ceremonies, yes.

339
00:24:10,560 --> 00:24:13,280
Um, this is quite unexpected.

340
00:24:13,320 --> 00:24:16,280
A lot of early collections of Birds of Paradise

341
00:24:16,320 --> 00:24:19,840
and other bird species that are found in Papua New Guinea

342
00:24:19,880 --> 00:24:23,600
came from headdresses which were sort of taken by explorers

343
00:24:23,640 --> 00:24:25,440
and brought back to the west,

344
00:24:25,480 --> 00:24:28,960
and in those early days when they saw feathers like those,

345
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:31,800
ornithologists just thought it was fakery,

346
00:24:31,840 --> 00:24:35,720
that it couldn't be a bird that had such spectacular feathers.

347
00:24:54,600 --> 00:24:57,000
I've made myself a little pit here

348
00:24:57,040 --> 00:24:59,480
and my sleeping bag ready to go.

349
00:24:59,520 --> 00:25:03,640
Tackle bag and half a carry mat, what more could a man ask for?

350
00:25:03,680 --> 00:25:07,600
The cavers have found a place for the night, but they're not alone.

351
00:25:10,040 --> 00:25:12,840
That is really weird.

352
00:25:12,880 --> 00:25:15,520
This is a freshwater crab from the outside

353
00:25:15,560 --> 00:25:18,240
and I would guess that it's probably been swept in here

354
00:25:18,280 --> 00:25:20,920
right from where the water's gathered for this cave.

355
00:25:20,960 --> 00:25:23,840
What's incredible though, to me,

356
00:25:23,880 --> 00:25:26,200
is if you look at it close up,

357
00:25:26,240 --> 00:25:29,400
its' absolutely covered in parasites.

358
00:25:29,440 --> 00:25:31,800
Rather grotesque white blobs

359
00:25:31,840 --> 00:25:36,320
which are kind of moving all over it, I mean look at those.

360
00:25:36,360 --> 00:25:38,960
I've never seen anything like this before in my life.

361
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:41,360
It really lends to the sense

362
00:25:41,400 --> 00:25:46,160
this place has of being just like an alien landscape.

363
00:25:53,760 --> 00:26:00,000
It's enticing to think from here quite how much is unexplored,

364
00:26:00,040 --> 00:26:03,240
that's like what we've seen so far in this area.

365
00:26:03,280 --> 00:26:05,560
It's probably riddled with caves like this

366
00:26:05,600 --> 00:26:09,200
and some of them will never see the light of day, and never be explored.

367
00:26:09,240 --> 00:26:12,040
The team desperately need their rest.

368
00:26:12,080 --> 00:26:16,600
But in a small damp cave under a million tonnes of rock,

369
00:26:16,640 --> 00:26:18,800
sleep may not come easily.

370
00:26:29,200 --> 00:26:32,600
In the village, a tribal dance begins.

371
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:34,680
THEY CHANT

372
00:26:40,040 --> 00:26:43,080
You've got everything that represents light and life in the forests.

373
00:26:43,120 --> 00:26:47,640
These guys wearing spectacular headdresses, Birds of Paradise,

374
00:26:47,680 --> 00:26:50,680
cockatoos, hornbills, all this sort of lush vegetation

375
00:26:50,720 --> 00:26:52,600
they've adorned themselves with.

376
00:26:54,160 --> 00:26:56,440
Centre stage are the feathers

377
00:26:56,480 --> 00:27:00,960
from one of the largest birds of paradise, the Raggianna.

378
00:27:03,640 --> 00:27:05,880
These are from Raggianna.

379
00:27:05,920 --> 00:27:09,080
Raggianna Bird of Paradise. And if you just look at the...

380
00:27:09,120 --> 00:27:14,440
Better from this angle. They look as if they've been doctored.

381
00:27:14,480 --> 00:27:17,720
They're just very un-feather like but very exquisite

382
00:27:17,760 --> 00:27:22,040
and that's just a small proportion of the feathers that are on this bird.

383
00:27:23,600 --> 00:27:26,560
If you think these costumes are elaborate,

384
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:30,160
they are nothing compared to the birds themselves.

385
00:27:30,200 --> 00:27:34,760
This is a sort of an imitation of their splendour.

386
00:27:53,960 --> 00:27:56,440
WHISPERS: I've just woken up in the middle of the night.

387
00:27:56,480 --> 00:27:59,560
Well, I think it's the middle of the night, could be any time really.

388
00:27:59,600 --> 00:28:04,600
Bit sort of tossing and turning with weird dreams

389
00:28:04,640 --> 00:28:09,320
about scuttling white cave crabs and things.

390
00:28:10,880 --> 00:28:13,320
I've suddenly picked up a fever,

391
00:28:13,360 --> 00:28:16,680
I've had the shakes, very high temperature,

392
00:28:16,720 --> 00:28:22,160
and a couple of sort of weak panic attacks with it as well.

393
00:28:22,200 --> 00:28:24,720
I feel absolutely awful.

394
00:28:27,680 --> 00:28:31,000
Just typical that it would happen tonight.

395
00:28:31,040 --> 00:28:34,360
Lie back down and try and get a bit more sleep

396
00:28:34,400 --> 00:28:38,840
but just can't wait for the morning and get out, really.

397
00:28:48,760 --> 00:28:52,320
At daybreak, Gordon sets off with trackers from the village

398
00:28:52,360 --> 00:28:55,880
looking for birds of paradise that are displaying.

399
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:03,840
The one saving grace we have is that Birds of Paradise are very vocal.

400
00:29:03,880 --> 00:29:05,680
We want to see them displaying

401
00:29:05,720 --> 00:29:07,600
which will give us an indication

402
00:29:07,640 --> 00:29:10,480
that they are in this area and they are breeding.

403
00:29:10,520 --> 00:29:13,520
I'm hoping that we can hear those sounds

404
00:29:13,560 --> 00:29:17,760
and zone in on them and find the birds based on their calls.

405
00:29:25,920 --> 00:29:27,720
It's definitely getting rougher.

406
00:29:31,440 --> 00:29:33,720
Pouring down from Mount Bosavi

407
00:29:33,760 --> 00:29:37,120
is a network of rivers that they must cross.

408
00:29:44,720 --> 00:29:47,120
So, how are we going to get across this?

409
00:29:47,160 --> 00:29:49,160
We will use a log to make a bridge.

410
00:29:49,200 --> 00:29:52,160
Put a log across, there's no way to walk round, no?

411
00:29:53,880 --> 00:29:58,720
They swim when they can, but the camera gear must be kept dry.

412
00:30:01,360 --> 00:30:04,480
They've managed to get that over but if you fell in there

413
00:30:04,520 --> 00:30:06,600
with a backpack on, you'd be a goner.

414
00:30:30,760 --> 00:30:35,360
Deep underground, Steve Backshall is going nowhere.

415
00:30:35,400 --> 00:30:40,240
I still have a really heavy fever and it was spiking in the night.

416
00:30:40,280 --> 00:30:43,000
I was actually hallucinating it was that bad.

417
00:30:43,040 --> 00:30:47,480
I just feel like I want everyone else to go out

418
00:30:47,520 --> 00:30:49,760
and just leave me here.

419
00:30:49,800 --> 00:30:52,080
That's not an option though, is it?

420
00:30:52,120 --> 00:30:54,040
Well, it's not really an option,

421
00:30:54,080 --> 00:30:59,000
no, but I feel absolutely desperate.

422
00:30:59,040 --> 00:31:01,640
Tim Fogg is in charge of safety.

423
00:31:01,680 --> 00:31:06,000
It's his job to get Steve out of the cave.

424
00:31:06,040 --> 00:31:08,880
This is a very, very remote place.

425
00:31:08,920 --> 00:31:10,520
We're a long way from home.

426
00:31:10,560 --> 00:31:14,480
We're going to have to help them as much as we can,

427
00:31:14,520 --> 00:31:19,200
but basically he's going to need to get out under his own steam.

428
00:31:21,960 --> 00:31:24,200
Even though the water's warm,

429
00:31:24,240 --> 00:31:27,320
it still gets to you a bit after a while.

430
00:31:27,360 --> 00:31:30,720
Steve is weak and running a high temperature.

431
00:31:30,760 --> 00:31:34,360
Lets go, Steve. Let's go, mate, straight through here.

432
00:31:34,400 --> 00:31:36,080
You all right?

433
00:31:36,120 --> 00:31:38,880
Come on, mate, you're doing great.

434
00:31:49,800 --> 00:31:55,040
Calling from the canopy is a King Bird of Paradise.

435
00:31:55,080 --> 00:31:57,000
Gordon's found a display site.

436
00:32:09,800 --> 00:32:11,280
It's right here, come over.

437
00:32:13,320 --> 00:32:18,720
Fortunately, the King does his courting close to the ground.

438
00:32:18,760 --> 00:32:21,360
Oh, yeah, there he is.

439
00:32:21,400 --> 00:32:24,720
I'm hoping that this is him getting ready for his big display,

440
00:32:24,760 --> 00:32:27,600
just making sure that all his feathers are in order.

441
00:32:27,640 --> 00:32:31,440
Great, now that's just the start of the display

442
00:32:31,480 --> 00:32:34,880
as he jumps from either side of the branch.

443
00:32:34,920 --> 00:32:37,000
These tail wires whack back and forward

444
00:32:37,040 --> 00:32:39,360
and that's attracting the female even more.

445
00:32:39,400 --> 00:32:44,400
Oh... duck down again. Oh, there he is right out in the open.

446
00:32:44,440 --> 00:32:47,800
OK, he's started displaying.

447
00:32:47,840 --> 00:32:49,640
He's brought the little tail

448
00:32:49,680 --> 00:32:52,720
that he does have right up to flat with his back,

449
00:32:52,760 --> 00:32:55,920
and tail wires are kind of dangling about over his head,

450
00:32:55,960 --> 00:32:58,480
and he's sort of jiggling back and forwards.

451
00:32:58,520 --> 00:33:01,480
There must be a female up there.

452
00:33:01,520 --> 00:33:05,200
On, yeah, there we go, there's a female.

453
00:33:05,240 --> 00:33:09,240
Gosh, you wouldn't even think that that was the same species.

454
00:33:18,280 --> 00:33:23,120
It's very easy to relate to this Bird of Paradise behaviour

455
00:33:23,160 --> 00:33:27,160
because it pretty much mimics what a lot of men do

456
00:33:27,200 --> 00:33:29,720
is to show off to attract women.

457
00:33:29,760 --> 00:33:33,640
It's the kind of disco scenario, the best dancer,

458
00:33:33,680 --> 00:33:40,280
the best dressed man sort of gets the best choice of the women, he gets the best women.

459
00:33:40,320 --> 00:33:42,680
Very easy to understand.

460
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:48,280
Amazing.

461
00:33:50,200 --> 00:33:52,440
Practically every life form

462
00:33:52,480 --> 00:33:56,560
that lives in this rainforest depends on the forest.

463
00:33:56,600 --> 00:33:59,960
You lose the forest, you lose the animals just like that,

464
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:02,080
it's a very, very simple equation.

465
00:34:02,120 --> 00:34:04,760
You can't have one without the other.

466
00:34:04,800 --> 00:34:08,560
And that's the terrible thing about deforestation.

467
00:34:08,600 --> 00:34:11,880
You're not just losing the trees you're losing this habitat

468
00:34:11,920 --> 00:34:13,840
and everything that depends on it.

469
00:34:21,880 --> 00:34:24,840
In the lab, the scientists are finding yet more evidence

470
00:34:24,880 --> 00:34:26,560
of the richness of this forest.

471
00:34:28,120 --> 00:34:32,920
Satellite images reveal just how rapidly jungle is disappearing.

472
00:34:34,480 --> 00:34:40,720
This is the scariest series of images that I think I've ever seen.

473
00:34:40,760 --> 00:34:42,560
This is pristine rainforest

474
00:34:42,600 --> 00:34:45,720
that has existed in this area for 10,000 years.

475
00:34:45,760 --> 00:34:49,120
16 years ago it looked like that,

476
00:34:49,160 --> 00:34:52,080
virtually untouched.

477
00:34:52,120 --> 00:34:56,560
And the most up-to-date image shows the road for forestry vehicles

478
00:34:56,600 --> 00:34:59,280
which are coming in to extract the wood,

479
00:34:59,320 --> 00:35:03,880
now spreading like veins all over the forest,

480
00:35:03,920 --> 00:35:07,400
and this is only 20 miles from here.

481
00:35:09,600 --> 00:35:13,640
This makes the mission to explore Bosavi's forests

482
00:35:13,680 --> 00:35:15,320
all the more urgent.

483
00:35:15,360 --> 00:35:18,040
I think the thing that's really striking about this

484
00:35:18,080 --> 00:35:19,600
is the incredible diversity,

485
00:35:19,640 --> 00:35:22,080
so every time you turn a corner you see a new insect,

486
00:35:22,120 --> 00:35:23,160
you see a new frog,

487
00:35:23,200 --> 00:35:25,520
you see a new beetle and that's the fun of it.

488
00:35:27,440 --> 00:35:31,320
George has been mesmerized by his mysterious caterpillars.

489
00:35:32,960 --> 00:35:37,000
At last, they're starting to pupate.

490
00:35:37,040 --> 00:35:40,920
There is one of the little caterpillars.

491
00:35:40,960 --> 00:35:43,800
It's hidden away on this folded leaf

492
00:35:43,840 --> 00:35:47,080
and it's also taken a bit of this dry leaf,

493
00:35:47,120 --> 00:35:51,200
and it's used a bit of silk, and it's now just hiding.

494
00:35:51,240 --> 00:35:56,920
Now I'm assuming what it'll do now is to pupate.

495
00:35:56,960 --> 00:35:59,720
But wouldn't it be great to be here when those hatched out

496
00:35:59,760 --> 00:36:05,080
and then we'd at last know what this amazing animal becomes as an adult.

497
00:36:14,560 --> 00:36:17,840
At Mageni, the cavers have reached the surface camp

498
00:36:17,880 --> 00:36:19,920
and Steve's fever is subsiding.

499
00:36:22,440 --> 00:36:28,120
The rest of the team also need time to recover.

500
00:36:33,280 --> 00:36:39,480
I have a kind of a rash on my body, just like burning my whole body.

501
00:36:39,520 --> 00:36:42,840
It's not very nice.

502
00:36:44,920 --> 00:36:48,680
Steve's gaining strength and keen to get back to the job.

503
00:36:48,720 --> 00:36:50,360
Before they go into the cave,

504
00:36:50,400 --> 00:36:53,120
they're adding their new data to the computer.

505
00:36:53,160 --> 00:36:54,440
In the 21st century,

506
00:36:54,480 --> 00:36:58,760
it's rare to be able to explore and chart a whole new river system.

507
00:36:58,800 --> 00:37:02,600
Well, this crunches all the numbers that we get when we go surveying,

508
00:37:02,640 --> 00:37:06,680
and very cleverly creates a 3D model of the cave.

509
00:37:06,720 --> 00:37:09,080
And it's by no means fully explored

510
00:37:09,120 --> 00:37:11,080
and there's various leads on here,

511
00:37:11,120 --> 00:37:13,720
these little dead ends or look like dead ends,

512
00:37:13,760 --> 00:37:16,560
these are passages that we didn't explore fully

513
00:37:16,600 --> 00:37:18,400
and are waiting to be surveyed.

514
00:37:18,440 --> 00:37:22,440
And it's just a matter of getting there and doing it and that's what burns a hole in my head.

515
00:37:24,920 --> 00:37:26,840
The lure of the cave is strong.

516
00:37:26,880 --> 00:37:32,000
Fired up again, the team drop back down the cliff side.

517
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:45,760
Truly, this is the land of the unexpected.

518
00:37:50,440 --> 00:37:53,400
On the eastern slopes of Mount Bosavi,

519
00:37:53,440 --> 00:37:55,800
Gordon is still tracking birds

520
00:37:55,840 --> 00:37:59,760
when he discovers a river erupting from deep underground.

521
00:38:02,360 --> 00:38:06,600
This is a place with lots of strange things

522
00:38:06,640 --> 00:38:09,680
and this is another one of them.

523
00:38:09,720 --> 00:38:12,640
This is the start of a river, a river that...

524
00:38:12,680 --> 00:38:17,560
well, actually, no, it's not the start because this river is flowing underground.

525
00:38:17,600 --> 00:38:19,960
It is just very peculiar.

526
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:22,800
All of this water getting pushed,

527
00:38:22,840 --> 00:38:28,680
a huge quantity of water that's flowing down from Bosavi underground

528
00:38:28,720 --> 00:38:31,680
into a big channel that wells up here.

529
00:38:31,720 --> 00:38:37,320
And I would say that this is the best example of the power of water

530
00:38:37,360 --> 00:38:41,760
and unseen goings on, things that are going on way beneath our feet.

531
00:38:50,760 --> 00:38:54,640
And then, at last, high in the trees above Gordon,

532
00:38:54,680 --> 00:38:57,080
the sound he's been hoping for.

533
00:38:59,120 --> 00:39:02,520
It is a Raggianna Bird Of Paradise calling.

534
00:39:02,560 --> 00:39:06,280
This time of day it will still be displaying.

535
00:39:06,320 --> 00:39:08,600
It's great to know that they're in here,

536
00:39:08,640 --> 00:39:11,120
and it's definitely one I want to try and film

537
00:39:11,160 --> 00:39:13,400
cos they are gobsmackingly beautiful.

538
00:39:16,080 --> 00:39:20,600
The Raggianna displays only in the treetops.

539
00:39:20,640 --> 00:39:24,760
Gordon shoots a line 20 metres up a nearby tree.

540
00:39:24,800 --> 00:39:28,800
He'll have to haul himself and all his kit up into the canopy.

541
00:39:30,880 --> 00:39:36,200
Few people have ever seen a Bird Of Paradise, let alone, you know,

542
00:39:36,240 --> 00:39:41,080
sat up in a treetop with them so there is a real sense of privilege.

543
00:39:48,080 --> 00:39:52,880
Gordon must move quietly, so he doesn't drive the birds away.

544
00:40:01,920 --> 00:40:03,600
Oh, bats!

545
00:40:03,640 --> 00:40:05,560
Lots of them.

546
00:40:05,600 --> 00:40:08,360
Steve and the cavers are back in Mageni,

547
00:40:08,400 --> 00:40:12,560
retracing their steps to where their exploration left off.

548
00:40:18,440 --> 00:40:20,640
Oh, yeah!

549
00:40:20,680 --> 00:40:24,960
And it's not long before their effort pay off.

550
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:31,120
Just found a lead.What, a new passage? Fantastic!I know, I know.

551
00:40:31,160 --> 00:40:33,400
If you look down there you can see the river.

552
00:40:33,440 --> 00:40:36,520
Oh, my god, it's a proper river.

553
00:40:36,560 --> 00:40:39,160
Yeah, no-one's been down there ever.

554
00:40:39,200 --> 00:40:40,960
We're the first people here.

555
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:43,160
There's a waterfall down there.

556
00:40:43,200 --> 00:40:46,000
Come on, without further ado.

557
00:40:49,840 --> 00:40:54,560
This new passage is drawing them down a side channel of the main river.

558
00:40:56,560 --> 00:41:00,360
Oh, I'm soaking!

559
00:41:00,400 --> 00:41:03,440
It's steep and it's getting narrower

560
00:41:03,480 --> 00:41:07,080
but it could be a new way out of the mountain.

561
00:41:07,120 --> 00:41:09,240
I don't know if you can make this out,

562
00:41:09,280 --> 00:41:11,680
we haven't really got enough light to show,

563
00:41:11,720 --> 00:41:14,760
but we're sitting at the top of a white water cataract

564
00:41:14,800 --> 00:41:17,360
which is raging off down into the mountain.

565
00:41:17,400 --> 00:41:20,160
And we're going to tread really carefully but I think,

566
00:41:20,200 --> 00:41:23,000
do you think, Moose, we should try and push on a little bit?

567
00:41:23,040 --> 00:41:26,240
Stick to the right-hand side and then we'll cross over.OK.

568
00:41:31,280 --> 00:41:33,800
In his treetop, Gordon is in position

569
00:41:33,840 --> 00:41:35,920
but everything is against him.

570
00:41:35,960 --> 00:41:38,080
BUZZING

571
00:41:38,120 --> 00:41:40,960
Bloody bees!

572
00:41:46,400 --> 00:41:47,440
Get off.

573
00:41:47,480 --> 00:41:50,480
He's level with the Raggianna display site

574
00:41:50,520 --> 00:41:52,440
but the heavens have opened.

575
00:41:54,400 --> 00:41:57,960
Little chance of these birds showing up.

576
00:41:59,520 --> 00:42:01,960
It's pouring down and apparently

577
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:05,840
Birds of Paradise don't like to display in the rain.

578
00:42:05,880 --> 00:42:11,200
I can hear them off... There you go, there's one. BIRD CHIRPS

579
00:42:11,240 --> 00:42:16,600
But the chances of them coming in and doing their stuff, I would say, would be very slim.

580
00:42:16,640 --> 00:42:19,600
Come on, you monkey.

581
00:42:22,520 --> 00:42:25,240
Oh. Jeez, there's one there. There's one there.

582
00:42:25,280 --> 00:42:29,200
Oh, you little darling.

583
00:42:30,800 --> 00:42:36,240
Oh, jeez, there's two of them, there's' two of them!

584
00:42:36,280 --> 00:42:38,240
Wow! Look at that.

585
00:42:40,040 --> 00:42:43,480
Despite the rain, there are two males trying to outshine each other.

586
00:42:43,520 --> 00:42:48,840
That is the most weird and fantastic bird I've ever seen.

587
00:42:48,880 --> 00:42:52,080
What's going on, what's going on?

588
00:42:52,120 --> 00:42:55,200
They're trying to show who's the fittest

589
00:42:55,240 --> 00:42:57,760
with a complicated dance routine.

590
00:43:00,040 --> 00:43:02,360
Wow!

591
00:43:02,400 --> 00:43:07,560
It almost looks as if the males are showing off to each other.

592
00:43:07,600 --> 00:43:10,040
OK, there must be a female around.

593
00:43:10,080 --> 00:43:15,920
Until a female turns up, these males can't afford to stop their display

594
00:43:15,960 --> 00:43:20,040
and Gordon can't afford to take his eyes off them.

595
00:43:20,080 --> 00:43:24,720
There's a huge volume of water pushing through here.

596
00:43:24,760 --> 00:43:27,840
It's a good job the ground's grippy.

597
00:43:27,880 --> 00:43:31,840
In the cave, the route they found is getting treacherous.

598
00:43:31,880 --> 00:43:35,200
You're best standing on the ridge, that's it.

599
00:43:35,240 --> 00:43:37,400
This is no place to lose your grip.

600
00:43:37,440 --> 00:43:41,440
Oh, look at that. We're going to cross here.

601
00:43:45,720 --> 00:43:51,560
This is extraordinary. It's a real raging, raging river.

602
00:43:51,600 --> 00:43:55,160
There's an incredible amount of water passing through here.

603
00:43:55,200 --> 00:43:58,360
If you actually lost your footing and got swept away down there,

604
00:43:58,400 --> 00:44:01,920
you could get sucked into a place where the water just goes underground

605
00:44:01,960 --> 00:44:05,240
with no air or you could just get swept over the top of a waterfall.

606
00:44:05,280 --> 00:44:08,880
Same time, though, this has got to be one of the most exciting things I've ever done.

607
00:44:08,920 --> 00:44:15,600
Every single step we take is new, no-one's ever seen any of this.

608
00:44:21,920 --> 00:44:25,520
Finding and exploring a brand new underground route

609
00:44:25,560 --> 00:44:28,120
is the ultimate thrill for any caver.

610
00:44:28,160 --> 00:44:31,200
It's a waterfall.

611
00:44:31,240 --> 00:44:33,200
We're in the top of a waterfall.

612
00:44:33,240 --> 00:44:36,280
You can hear the noise of it. It's like a 747 taking off.

613
00:44:38,680 --> 00:44:41,080
The passage goes off in that direction

614
00:44:41,120 --> 00:44:43,560
so we've got some more exploring to do.

615
00:44:43,600 --> 00:44:46,400
That's fantastic!

616
00:44:46,440 --> 00:44:50,720
To descend any further, they'll need climbing equipment.

617
00:44:50,760 --> 00:44:53,760
The guys have kindly said I could go first,

618
00:44:53,800 --> 00:44:57,960
so I'm going to head down, see what we can find down there.

619
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:01,040
See you at the bottom, mate.

620
00:45:09,840 --> 00:45:13,840
This is an absolutely awesome place.

621
00:45:13,880 --> 00:45:15,120
It's just thunderous.

622
00:45:15,160 --> 00:45:17,160
Honestly, just the noise of it

623
00:45:17,200 --> 00:45:20,040
makes you feel like you're being battered the entire time.

624
00:45:20,080 --> 00:45:24,680
Heading down there now, into the unknown.

625
00:45:32,760 --> 00:45:35,040
Go, go, go, go!

626
00:45:35,080 --> 00:45:40,640
That is the biggest scorpion I have seen yet here.

627
00:45:40,680 --> 00:45:43,600
In the jungle, George is out collecting.

628
00:45:45,160 --> 00:45:48,000
Come on, we want something nice.

629
00:45:48,040 --> 00:45:50,480
The base camp phase of the expedition is nearing an end

630
00:45:50,520 --> 00:45:54,880
but the forest is still delivering surprises.

631
00:45:54,920 --> 00:45:59,320
There's a little tiny frog, a little tiny frog just sitting on that leaf.

632
00:45:59,360 --> 00:46:02,800
Think we should collect that for Alan, our frog expert.

633
00:46:05,080 --> 00:46:07,920
Alan, I bring you frog.

634
00:46:07,960 --> 00:46:11,600
Is it a tree frog, very sort of adhesive little feet?

635
00:46:13,160 --> 00:46:16,720
Indeed it is a tree frog. It's an interesting one, this is a great one.

636
00:46:16,760 --> 00:46:20,040
Wow, it's the first one we've found here, we have not found this yet.

637
00:46:20,080 --> 00:46:24,120
It could either be a new species or on it's way to being a new species.

638
00:46:24,160 --> 00:46:26,080
Yes!Thank you so much.

639
00:46:28,400 --> 00:46:32,560
Across the lab, photographer Ulla has set up a time-lapse studio.

640
00:46:34,840 --> 00:46:38,640
That's looking so close.

641
00:46:38,680 --> 00:46:42,920
One of George's mystery caterpillars is now a chrysalis

642
00:46:42,960 --> 00:46:45,080
and could hatch at any time.

643
00:46:45,120 --> 00:46:50,160
What I really want is to give it a little poke just to see if it's...

644
00:46:50,200 --> 00:46:53,000
I can't just give it a little poke, no?

645
00:46:53,040 --> 00:46:58,920
Well, no, it would really spoil the time lapse, so sorry.

646
00:47:02,440 --> 00:47:05,240
The cameras should capture the very moment it emerges.

647
00:47:06,800 --> 00:47:08,680
I know what's going to happen.

648
00:47:08,720 --> 00:47:12,720
It'll emerge and it'll be the most tedious, boring little moth.

649
00:47:32,080 --> 00:47:35,040
Oh, no, I don't like the look of this at all.

650
00:47:36,600 --> 00:47:38,600
This is the way on...

651
00:47:38,640 --> 00:47:41,040
Well, possibly.

652
00:47:41,080 --> 00:47:43,960
The water seems to have levelled out a little bit

653
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:46,600
and it goes underneath a narrow ceiling here,

654
00:47:46,640 --> 00:47:49,360
and it looks like there might be more beyond it.

655
00:47:50,920 --> 00:47:53,200
What do you reckon, Moose?

656
00:47:53,240 --> 00:47:57,200
I reckon it's a duck of about four-five metres.

657
00:47:57,240 --> 00:47:59,880
You know this is about the worse thing you could do

658
00:47:59,920 --> 00:48:02,360
is to go into the unknown in fast-flowing water,

659
00:48:02,400 --> 00:48:04,080
cos you get whisked away, yeah?

660
00:48:13,120 --> 00:48:16,040
Only Steve and Moose will press on into the unknown.

661
00:48:16,080 --> 00:48:18,280
The rest of the team can only wait.

662
00:48:34,280 --> 00:48:39,000
In the tree top, Gordon's two male Raggiannas are upping their game.

663
00:48:42,120 --> 00:48:44,960
Their efforts have attracted a potential mate.

664
00:48:47,280 --> 00:48:49,720
Oh, there you go, female.

665
00:48:49,760 --> 00:48:52,960
She'll decide which is her favourite.

666
00:48:59,400 --> 00:49:04,480
Now this could get quite interesting.

667
00:49:04,520 --> 00:49:05,840
Despite the rain,

668
00:49:05,880 --> 00:49:11,080
they're both putting in this display because there's competition.

669
00:49:11,120 --> 00:49:13,200
And not only is there competition,

670
00:49:13,240 --> 00:49:16,640
there is a female around and that's what it's all about.

671
00:49:16,680 --> 00:49:18,760
Oh, man,

672
00:49:18,800 --> 00:49:21,880
doesn't get much better than this.

673
00:49:21,920 --> 00:49:23,840
Not when it comes to birds.

674
00:49:23,880 --> 00:49:25,720
Oh, two females! Jeez.

675
00:49:25,760 --> 00:49:29,440
A second female also shows an interest.

676
00:49:29,480 --> 00:49:31,480
Come on, I see what you can get.

677
00:49:31,520 --> 00:49:35,960
Oh, he's pecking her, oh easy on.

678
00:49:38,640 --> 00:49:43,680
This is quite incredible

679
00:49:43,720 --> 00:49:48,720
that these birds have evolved to look like this, to sound like this,

680
00:49:48,760 --> 00:49:51,240
to act like this just to win a mate.

681
00:49:52,800 --> 00:49:56,760
Well, it looks as if she's decided who she likes.

682
00:49:56,800 --> 00:50:02,880
Oh, yes, you will be mine.

683
00:50:08,960 --> 00:50:13,080
As one male makes the biggest impression, the second knows he's beaten.

684
00:50:14,680 --> 00:50:17,520
Oh, mating, he's mating, oh, lovely.

685
00:50:22,240 --> 00:50:24,360
Oh, I can't believe we've got that.

686
00:50:24,400 --> 00:50:28,960
Now I wonder if he'll actually mate with both of them in the one day.

687
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:34,560
This male's done well, he's won over the second female.

688
00:50:34,600 --> 00:50:36,680
She is not boring at all.

689
00:50:36,720 --> 00:50:38,640
He looks really doing his stuff.

690
00:50:45,440 --> 00:50:49,000
That's what it's all about with Birds of Paradise,

691
00:50:49,040 --> 00:50:53,600
is if you look that great you're going to get more than one lady.

692
00:50:55,960 --> 00:50:58,440
And off she goes.

693
00:50:58,480 --> 00:51:03,280
You don't really get too many days like this.

694
00:51:03,320 --> 00:51:06,680
Off he goes, beautiful. Ta-da.

695
00:51:15,840 --> 00:51:18,120
Oh, lord. This goes on forever.

696
00:51:20,880 --> 00:51:26,080
Steve and Moose have been alone inside the flooded cave for 15 minutes.

697
00:51:28,560 --> 00:51:31,640
The river's deep and the ceiling is getting lower.

698
00:51:31,680 --> 00:51:35,640
It's not as hectic as it was the other side.

699
00:51:35,680 --> 00:51:39,080
But it's still running quite fast.

700
00:51:39,120 --> 00:51:42,960
Then the river disappears into an airless chamber.

701
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:47,520
As far as exploration of this part of the cave is concerned,

702
00:51:47,560 --> 00:51:49,520
this is the end of the line.

703
00:51:49,560 --> 00:51:52,920
Don't want to get washed into a watery grave down there,

704
00:51:52,960 --> 00:51:54,600
so let's not go any further.

705
00:51:54,640 --> 00:51:57,360
There's no way the cavers can go on.

706
00:51:59,320 --> 00:52:02,360
There's nothing more here for us. Let's head out.

707
00:52:05,360 --> 00:52:08,240
You know, we've reached the end, that's what we came here to do.

708
00:52:08,280 --> 00:52:11,480
We've actually found the end of this piece of passage,

709
00:52:11,520 --> 00:52:13,760
and now I think it's time to head home.

710
00:52:13,800 --> 00:52:16,720
The caving has been a success.

711
00:52:16,760 --> 00:52:21,240
They've found and charted a section of cave never before seen.

712
00:52:21,280 --> 00:52:25,640
But for Steve, the expedition is far from over.

713
00:52:40,120 --> 00:52:44,720
While George is asleep in his hammock, something stirs in the lab.

714
00:52:45,760 --> 00:52:51,880
The time-lapse camera watches as a moth chooses its moment to emerge.

715
00:53:05,480 --> 00:53:08,160
George?

716
00:53:17,280 --> 00:53:21,120
Oh, that's beautiful, look at that!

717
00:53:21,160 --> 00:53:22,960
Absolutely...

718
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:24,520
please don't fly off.

719
00:53:26,600 --> 00:53:31,720
I have never seen a moth like this before in my life.

720
00:53:31,760 --> 00:53:34,080
Don't fly off, please don't fly off.

721
00:53:34,120 --> 00:53:38,680
Just look at the pattern on the back of that wing.

722
00:53:38,720 --> 00:53:40,600
Wow, they are amazing.

723
00:53:40,640 --> 00:53:42,800
When you see something in the wild

724
00:53:42,840 --> 00:53:46,160
and you don't know if it'll be a moth or what sort of moth,

725
00:53:46,200 --> 00:53:50,320
and the only way of finding out what any immature stage will become

726
00:53:50,360 --> 00:53:53,280
is to rear them up, which is exactly what we did.

727
00:53:53,320 --> 00:53:58,320
My wife has her birthday today and I'm not there,

728
00:53:58,360 --> 00:54:05,320
and if these turn out to be new species, I will name them after her.

729
00:54:05,360 --> 00:54:07,800
I really hope they are new species.

730
00:54:13,920 --> 00:54:19,120
In base camp, Steve is preparing for the next challenge of the expedition.

731
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:27,560
The team's new destination is the volcanic crater of Mount Bosavi.

732
00:54:30,200 --> 00:54:34,920
Its fortress walls have kept the hunters out and animals in.

733
00:54:36,480 --> 00:54:40,760
This isolated cauldron could conceal spectacular new species.

734
00:54:40,800 --> 00:54:43,240
Steve, look at that.

735
00:54:43,280 --> 00:54:46,240
There it is, Mount Bosavi. I've got to say it's so much like

736
00:54:46,280 --> 00:54:49,120
something you'd expect to see in a geography textbook.

737
00:54:49,160 --> 00:54:53,480
This whole volcano is a million years old.

738
00:54:53,520 --> 00:54:57,240
The last time it blew up was 200,000 years ago.

739
00:54:57,280 --> 00:54:59,120
Yeah, sounds about right, so potentially

740
00:54:59,160 --> 00:55:02,200
everything that's in there's been trapped in there for 200,000 years.

741
00:55:02,240 --> 00:55:05,480
So the great thing is, of course, is that also if there is any hunting

742
00:55:05,520 --> 00:55:09,280
it tends to be done on the low-lying part.

743
00:55:09,320 --> 00:55:11,920
Who is going to climb up into the crater to hunt stuff

744
00:55:11,960 --> 00:55:16,480
when you don't have to, so this whole area is going to be really...

745
00:55:16,520 --> 00:55:18,240
Very, very exciting.

746
00:55:18,280 --> 00:55:24,200
You talk about lost worlds, well this is just, it doesn't get any better than this.It is amazing.

747
00:55:31,080 --> 00:55:33,240
Steve is leading the advance party,

748
00:55:33,280 --> 00:55:35,760
paving the way for the rest of the team.

749
00:55:35,800 --> 00:55:38,360
Come on, guys, good luck.

750
00:55:43,240 --> 00:55:47,920
They're going to build a camp right in the heart of the crater.

751
00:55:58,840 --> 00:56:02,560
The survey of the animals around base camp is now complete,

752
00:56:02,600 --> 00:56:04,080
and its time to move on.

753
00:56:08,040 --> 00:56:12,920
In just four weeks, the scientists have found and catalogued hundreds of animals.

754
00:56:12,960 --> 00:56:17,400
A staggering 29 are believed to be completely new to science.

755
00:56:21,720 --> 00:56:23,680
Yeah, the trip's been really great.

756
00:56:23,720 --> 00:56:27,680
We were able to get a lot of birds in the nets, a lot of bats as well working with Alanna.

757
00:56:27,720 --> 00:56:29,440
We have well over 90 species between us

758
00:56:29,480 --> 00:56:31,200
and I haven't even made the final total,

759
00:56:31,240 --> 00:56:33,000
it will probably be even more than that.

760
00:56:34,560 --> 00:56:37,920
The next destination is beyond the clouds.

761
00:56:39,560 --> 00:56:43,480
The ancient crater inside Mount Bosavi itself.

762
00:56:43,520 --> 00:56:49,080
They'll be the first scientists ever to explore this lost world.

763
00:57:01,280 --> 00:57:07,080
This is the crater rim we're about to cross now. And that is the crater.

764
00:57:09,080 --> 00:57:12,600
I didn't prepare myself for the size of it.

765
00:57:28,040 --> 00:57:30,040
All the wildlife, all the plants

766
00:57:30,080 --> 00:57:33,840
that are here have been trapped inside by all of these walls.

767
00:57:33,880 --> 00:57:37,720
It's almost like the inside of the crater is kind of like an island.

768
00:57:37,760 --> 00:57:41,960
We could find something really, really spectacular inside here.

769
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:44,840
I guess that's the hope.

770
00:57:47,160 --> 00:57:53,280
Next time, George witnesses the birth of a new mountain.

771
00:57:53,320 --> 00:57:58,520
To be absolutely honest with you I'm actually feeling quite apprehensive.

772
00:57:58,560 --> 00:58:03,560
You couldn't speed away from this in a hurry, you would be toast.

773
00:58:03,600 --> 00:58:08,640
In Bosavi's crater, the team find kangaroos that live in trees.

774
00:58:08,680 --> 00:58:11,520
The fact that this animal just wandered straight past us

775
00:58:11,560 --> 00:58:14,240
means the wildlife here has never been hunted before,

776
00:58:14,280 --> 00:58:15,720
it hasn't seen people before.

777
00:58:15,760 --> 00:58:19,680
And the most significant discovery of all, a new species

778
00:58:19,720 --> 00:58:24,000
of mammal, the largest of its kind anywhere in the world.

779
00:58:24,040 --> 00:58:26,240
Oh, my word, have a look at this.

780
00:58:26,280 --> 00:58:29,520
Oh, gosh!

